<font color="#FF0000">SANITY?</font><br>
<tt>Sat Dec 20 23:41:21 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br><br>
Not knowing much about you or your brother makes it hard to respond to your posts.  But I am going to give it a try anyway.  If I offend, it is not done intentionally.  I am only speaking from my experience.<br><br>
I am a fan of the star trek series (not enough so to count bottles on shelves in any episodes).  I believe there was a story in Star Trek the Next Generation about a society which was facing a war with an impressive enemy.  The leaders asked for volunteers who were then genetically reengineered to be super-soldiers.  The men went and fought the invaders and won.  Once the war was over, the society refused to let their men who were now viewed as too dangerous for polite society come home nor would they do anything to treat them and return them to the state they had been in before the reengineering so they would be less likely to get into fights.  The soldiers broke out from where they  were being held as captives and at gun point demanded to be allowed to rejoin their families and the society they fought to preserve.  A key to the story was that the men were honorable men and would only fight if threatened, but then they were fierce fighters.  <br><br>
The response you have seen here WFS is similar to the response that you would have seen in that episode.  Your statement after your initial question come across as threatening and hostile to the people you claim to be coming to for information to learn about your brother.<br><br>
The Vietnam Era lasted for a long time.  Depending upon when a person served, and where that person served they would have had very different experiences.  There was a time I understand when there were standdown parties in the rear areas and you could have been assigned in- country to play in a band in the rear for these parties.  I don't think that pomp and circumstance took place while I was in Nam, and it is hard for me to comprehend that this could have been someone's job in a war zone.  Life would have been very different for someone in a band or was a pilot than for the grunt in the field.  Even between grunts, there could have been considerable difference in life-style and physical threat depending upon whether you were someone who was in a special unit who spent weeks if not months on long-range patrols versus someone who came back to firebases periodically and had few engagements with the enemy.  If you want to learn about the brother you personally never got to know you need to start by identifying what his job was in the service, when he served in Vietnam, and which units he served with.  This will give you a better shot at learning what experiences he would have had and what kind of man he might have been and become.  <br><br>
I am not going to coddle you.  The boy that joined or was drafted into the service would not have been the man who returned had he not died in Vietnam.  The military and war changes a person.  I can't tell from your post whether you prefer to think of your brother as somehow better than the men you see here, or just as bad.  Living in the shadow of a deceased relative who in retrospect can do no wrong in your parents eyes must be a difficult shadow to stand in.  <br><br>
 I am guessing that &quot;waiting for sanity&quot; and  &quot;(anon) above are the same person in which case you plan to go back through the archives this weekend.  Try to keep an open mind and make your own judgements about the accuracy of  the name calling on this site.  There seems to be more than enough  blame to go around.  In the scriptures, Jesus said to the people who were planning to stone a woman for adultery to let the one who is among you without sin to cast the first stone.  There is enough guilt to go around.  I just hope we can all get our act together and be a bit more compassionate and understanding of each other.
<p><code>--   (Class Lass) </code><p>


